://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=61.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  The Machines Of Star Wars.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.popularmechanics.com/images/tw_starwars.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.popularmechanics.com/">Article from Popular Mechanics.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>We lift the hoods and pull back the access panels on the most amazing land- and spacecraft George Lucas has ever imagined.<br><br><br>As the world clammers to see &quot;Star Wars: Episode II–Attack Of The Clones,&quot; we invite you on our private tour of Skywalker Ranch and the machines of &quot;Episode I–The Phantom Menace.&quot;<br><br>Crammed into the subway-tight elevator, it occurs to us that there isn't a 12-year-old boy on the planet who wouldn't trade his best sneakers to be in our shoes. &quot;Half of the people who work here don't even know this place exists,&quot; says our escort as she turns a brass key in a lock on the control panel. &quot;They don't know there is a third floor.&quot; Even the CIA marks its elevator buttons. But then, they're not hiding a billion dollars' worth of alien technology. &quot;Star Wars&quot; creator George Lucas has invited POPULAR MECHANICS to Skywalker Ranch, just north of San Francisco, and given us unprecedented access to the Lucasfilm design studio. For the next few hours we will be lifting the hoods and kicking the tractor beams of the machines of &quot;Star Wars: Episode I–The Phantom Menace.&quot; Like the spacecraft of the &quot;Star Wars&quot; trilogy, the machines of &quot;Episode I&quot; sprang from Lucas's rich imagination. The job of making these impossible vehicles seem as real as the family minivan has fallen upon two young men whose own imaginations were sparked by the first &quot;Star Wars&quot; movies.<br><br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/aviation/1999/6/star_wars_machines/index.phtml">Click here for more.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 131<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/21/02 9:34:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=61.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The Machines Of Star Wars.</span><hr size=1> The naboo starships use a unique kind of fusion powered<br>nuclear electric ion drive for sublight propulsion.<br>In this type of ion drive there is a a ring shaped<br>ion collimation  grid at the back of the ion beam <br> ionziation  chamber, and then  there is an ion<br> accelerator  electrode that is in the shape of a<br> wedge with  a sharp point. The main electrostatic<br> ion beam accelerating  electric charge is placed on<br> the pionted end of this electrode. This creates the ring shaped ion engine exchaust of the naboo starships.<br>The naboo starships are made of metal such as titanium or <br>aluminium with high luster, and they use a delta winged<br>lifting body aerodynamic shape.The naboo starships also appear to be equipped with a bussard ion collector on the front end of their ion engines.  